{"id":"2103.16715","submitter":"Andrei Zelnikov","authors":"R. Krechetnikov and A. Zelnikov","title":"Lifshitz theory for a wedge","comments":"5 pages, 3 figures","journal-ref":"Phys.Rev.A 105 (2022) 2, 022802","doi":"10.1103/PhysRevA.105.022802","report-no":"Alberta Thy 37-21","categories":"hep-th","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We develop the Lifshitz theory of van der Waals forces in a wedge of a\ndielectric material. The non-planar geometry of the problem requires\ndetermining point-wise distribution of stresses. The findings are relevant to a\nwide range of phenomena from crack propagation to contact line motion. First,\nthe stresses prove to be anisotropic as opposed to the classical fluid\nmechanics treatment of the contact line problem. Second, the wedge\nconfiguration is always unstable with its angle tending either to collapse or\nunfold. The presented theory unequivocally demonstrates quantum nature of the\nforces dictating the wedge behavior, which cannot be accounted for with the\nclassical methods.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 30 Mar 2021 22:55:33 GMT"}],"update_date":"2022-02-18"}
